<HEAD>Pope Expected To Denounce Drugs, Poverty In Ninth Trip To
Continent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II starts his ninth trip to
South America on Saturday, a visit expected to focus on the
pontiff's campaign against drugs and poverty in the overwhelmingly
Roman Catholic continent.
   John Paul's 12-day itinerary will take him to Uruguay and Peru,
both for the second time, to impoverished Bolivia, high in the
Andes, and to a meeting in Paraguay with strongman Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner.
   The tour, John Paul's 37th foreign pilgrimage since he became
pope nine years ago, is a sign of the importance the Vatican gives
to an area expected to include half of the world's Roman Catholics
by the end of the century. The trip also leaves Cuba as the only
major country in the region not visited by the Polish-born pope.
   It will be a new test of the fitness of John Paul, who will turn
68 while in Paraguay on May 18. In addition to keeping to his usual
grueling schedule and delivering 60 speeches, he will make two
stops in the 2{-mile-high altitudes of Bolivia.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro said the pope's doctors
advised him to consider slowing down his pace at that altitude but
that John Paul replied: ``How can I do that?''
   The pope's first stop is Uruguay, considered the most secular
country in the region.
   John Paul then makes a five-day tour of Bolivia that will
include a stop in Santa Cruz, an eastern city where cocaine
traffickers are said to operate with near impunity.
   A U.S. congressional committee recently accused Bolivia, Peru
and Paraguay of failing to give the United States full cooperation
in the war on drugs. The House Foreign Affairs Committee voted to
impose aid sanctions. The legislation was considered unlikely to
pass before a May 13 deadline.
   The pope, who on his 1985 trip to Peru noted that Andean natives
have traditionally used coca leaves to ward off fatigue and hunger,
is expected to denounce the international problem of cocaine
smuggling.
   In a special edition on the upcoming trip, the Vatican newspaper
called Bolivia ``one of the most tormented countries'' in South
America because of its economic and social problems and said that
drug trafficking was ``eroding and polluting'' all levels of
society.
   After Bolivia, the pope travels to the Peruvian capital of Lima
to deliver the closing address to a regional religious conference.
   Church officials said that from his jet window as he nears
Lima's airport, the pontiff will be greeted with ``Papa Paz,'' _ or
``Pope Peace'' _ a giant sign made of white flowers set in a
25-acre potato patch.
   The greeting is a play on words, since ``papa'' is the Spanish
word for both pope and the potato. Officials said the pope, who
speaks Spanish fluently, will readily understand the message.
   Church officials expect about 2 million people to attend Mass in
a seaside field with a 115-foot illuminated cross.
   In Paraguay the pope is scheduled to meet with Stroessner on May
16, when he arrives in the capital of Asuncion.
   Stroessner, who came to power in an army coup in 1954, was
recently re-elected to an eighth presidential term with an
officially announced 88.6 percent of the vote. Opposition
politicians claimed the election was rigged.
   During his visit to Chile in 1987, John Paul came under
criticism for meeting with the country's authoritarian ruler, Gen.
Augusto Pinochet.
   The Vatican bristles at any suggestion that such meetings imply
the pope's support for a particular person or policy.
   ``He (the pope) doesn't consecrate any person or system,'' said
Navarro. ``He goes to visit the people.''
   The pope is scheduled to return to Rome on May 19.
</TEXT>
