<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, the Paraguayan, Bolivian, and Uruguayan 
foreign ministers relaunched Urupabol [Permanent Joint 
Commission of Uruguay, Paraguay, and Bolivia] -- 12 years after 
it disappeared -- as a way to strengthen the physical 
integration of the three countries. 
  After two days of meetings, at 1230 yesterday, Paraguayan 
Foreign Minister Luis Maria Ramirez Boettner, Bolivian Foreign 
Minister Antonio Aranibar Quiroga, and Uruguayan Foreign 
Minister Sergio Abreu Bonilla signed a joint declaration at the 
Foreign Ministry in Asuncion. 
  The ministers asked that the Agreement for River 
Transportation through the Paraguay-Parana Waterway be ratified 
by all member countries as a way to strengthen physical 
integration. Argentina and Brazil have yet to ratify the 
document. Paraguay, Bolivia, and Uruguay have already ratified 
it. 
  In the joint declaration, the foreign ministers express the 
need for a more significant participation of companies from the 
three Urupabol member countries in the implementation of the 
various Paraguay-Parana Waterway projects. The ministers agree 
that NAFTA is an important step forward for the creation of a 
broadened economic space in the hemisphere. 
  Uruguayan Foreign Minister Sergio Abreu Bonilla stressed 
that 
the relaunching of Urupabol -- which disappeared in 1982 -- does 
not seek to upset the influence of Argentina and Brazil, the two 
powerful Mercosur [Common Market of the South] member countries. 
The idea is to complement and compare interests, Abreu said. 
  The Paraguayan and Bolivian foreign ministers said they were 
pleased with the Uruguayan offer to use Uruguayan port 
facilities to take their products to the Atlantic Ocean. 

</TEXT>

